title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning  A Bolt .22 rifle
postcontent:
I'm selling my Browning A bolt .22 rifle. The rifle is a 1993 model I bought new. This rifle is the Grade 1 version. The A bolt rifle was discontinued in 1996  I think the next generation was the T bolt (not 100% sure on this).

The stock is a high gloss finished Premium Black Walnut wood and is checkered. The grip cap is Rose wood as is the front fore-end tip. The butt plate is black plastic. The barrel and receiver are finished with a high luster blue. 

The receiver is grooved for scope mounts. The gun has a smooth, fast operating bolt action with a 60-degree bolt rotation and the signature Browning A-bolt knob. The gold-plated trigger is user adjustable and the trigger guard/bottom iron is made of aluminum. 

The barrel is free floating. The standard detachable box magazine holds 5 cartridges. A 15 round magazine was available as an accessory. It also comes with a nylon camo sling. I do have the owners manual with it. This is obviously a premium rifle. 

The Scope is a Bushnell Sportview 4 power, 32 mm adjustable objective wide angle lens. This scope is designed for a .22 rifle. The objective lens is adjustable for a parallax free range from 7.5 yards to 100 yards. Most high powered rifle scopes start at 50 yards to infinity. 

The scope lens are fully coated, anti glare, fog proof and water proof. The windage and elevation adjusters are audible and resettable. The scope mounting rings are up graded from the standard scope rings that normally come with a .22 scope. 

This rifle will gain in value as it has over the past 20 years. Look at it as an investment as well as a super nice squirrel gun. I'm asking $700.00. I will entertain  trade offers. Maybe another lesser .22 rifle and some cash to boot?

title: For Sale:  Winchester 94 Flat Band Carbine (1947) 30WCF **PRICE DROP**
postcontent:
For sale is my Winchester 94 Flat Band Carbine, chambered in 30 WCF (30-30).  Rifles is excellent overall shape, and manufactured in 1947.  Slight blue wear can be seen around the lower edges of the receiver and around the muzzle.  There are a few light scratches on the sides of the receiver, nothing deep or that could be described as gouges.  Stock and forearm are in great condition, with no cracks or chips.  Mfg in 1947.  $750 or best offer. 

Now for a little history; the 94 Flat Band Carbines were produced for a portion of 1946, all of 1947 and a portion of 1948. The barrel band was flat instead of usual rounded and polished as a way for Winchester to make a part that didn't require extra machining and work to produce during WWII, when the factories were cranking out military arms. 

Please email with any other questions you may have.  Price is $700 or best offer.  Only partial trades I'm interested in would be a Noveske or KAC lower receiver in 5.56.  Thanks.

The only marks on it are from being taken in and out of the sheath, which is stated as being normal due to the tightness of the the sheath in the instructions included with the knife.  The Buck 184 "Buckmaster" is a large Bowie-bladed survival knife, allegedly developed at the request of the US Navy SEALs. The knife has a blade that is approximately 7.5" (19cm) long, and is of the classic Bowie shape. The hollow-ground main edge is about 6.5" (16.5cm) long. The false edge is serrated on one side. The back of the blade features a very aggressive 3" (7.5cm) long sawback. Maximum blade width is about 1.5" (3.7cm), and the blade is .288 - .290-inch thick. The blade is forged 425mod steel. The handguard is about 6mm thick, with both ends curving slightly towards the blade. Each end is drilled and tapped for a 2" (51mm) long, 10mm diameter "point" which is designed to allow the knife to be used as an anchor when a line is attached to the lanyard ring at the pommel. The grip is 4" (102mm) long and 1.25" (2.8cm) in diameter, knurled and grooved for a sure grip. The grip is hollow, with a usable internal opening secured by the threaded pommel, which in turn is knurled, slightly larger in diameter than the grip, and sealed with a black rubber O-ring. The threaded pommel also secured a 4.5mm thick steel stamping which is pierced to provide a lanyard/rope hole.
The sheath is of black rigid fiberglass-reinforced plastic. Attached to the front of the sheath is one removable black nylon pouch; it contains a full-size Silva Type 12 compass with a red cord lanyard. The back of the sheath has an inlaid sharpening stone. Heavy black nylon webbing is used to cover the stone, secure the two pouches to the sheath, secure the knife in its sheath, and provide a loop for a leg tie. An additional loop of black nylon webbing, with a Fastex-type closure, provides a quick-release belt loop.
Call Tony REDACTED

title: For Sale/Trade:  Astra A100 in 9mm
postcontent:
This is an Astra A100 in 9mm, which is Spain's version of the SIG P226. It is in
excellent condition and has a fresh cleaning. If you like the Euro-style handguns
(decocker with exposed hammer) that can tolerate any ammo, this is for you.

Included is the original box, manual, and two 17-round MEC-GAR magazines. This gun was new as of July 1996. I just had Raven Head Arms in Bellevue give this gun a trigger job last month.
You'll be hard-pressed to find a smoother operating semi-auto handgun in your lifetime.

It's never jammed no matter what i've used: Federal, Wolf, WPA, Magtech, CCI
Blazer Brass, Fiocchi, PPU, Herter's black box (Czech), Herter's beige box
(Russian - Tula), Herter's gray box (CCI aluminum), and Brown Bear. Accuracy is cheap with this, as it loves the Russian steel case ammo. For the record, the rebranded CCI aluminum TNJ (total nylon jacket) ammo sold at Cabela's under the Herter's name is freakishly accurate in this gun.
